4)-Baker shows how racial categories change over time.Baker paints a vivid picture of the relationships between specific African American and white scholars, who orchestrated a paradigm shift within the social sciences from ideas based on Social Darwinism to those based on cultural relativism. He demonstrates that the greatest impact on the way the law codifies racial differences has been made by organizations such as the NAACP, which skillfully appropriated the new social science to exploit the politics of the Cold War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxPublic opinion. 0aAnthropologiexHistoirexÉtats-Unis. 0aAnthropologyxHistoryxUnited States. 0aNoirs américainsxOpinion publique. 0aOpinion publiquexÉtats-Unis. 0aPublic opinionxUnited States. 0aRacism in anthropologyxHistoryxUnited States. 0aRacism in popular culturexHistoryxUnited States. 0aRacisme dans la culture populairexHistoirexÉtats-Unis. 0aRacisme en anthropologiexHistoirexÉtats-Unis. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press eBook Package Archivez978311063534840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520920194423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520920194.jpg  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles